Polybius, t e erni· nenthistorian, native of Megalopolis in Arcadia, was born about lac. 204. He was chief of the Achaean league after Philopoemen and one of the 1000 Achaeans sent to Rome to ans-wer the charge of not having assisted the Romans against Perseus. At Rome he remained serenteen years in the house of Aemilius Paulus, of whose son, Scipio Africanus minor, he became the friend, and joined him in his campaign at Carthage and was present at the destruction of that city lae. 146. His history, consisting of forty books, was divided into two parts. The first part comprises a period of fifty-three years, beginning with the second Punic war lae. 218, and ending with the conquest of the Macedonian kingdom ue. 168. The second part comprised the period from the conquest of Perseus to ,the fall of Corinth nc. 146. The passage here referred to is in a fragment of Book vr 56 ft. Livy xxn 61 says that according to one account they all remained behind in Rome, and only the three returned, whom Hannibal had sent after them, because they did not retum as soon as he expected.
